## Chapter 1: Project Background

### 1.1 Project Description

The PeBS Management System is a centralized, mobile-friendly web portal being developed for Penggerak Belia Selangor Zon 20 (PeBS Zon 20). As the approved Project Charter outlines, Pebs's current operations rely on manual processes and disconnected tools, resulting in inefficiencies in communication, event planning, member engagement, and reporting.

This project aims to streamline PeBS's zonal administrative functions by creating a digital platform that supports:

* Member directory with registration/login.

* Event calendar and RSVP management.

* News and announcement publishing.

* Feedback form tracking.

The development process started on 13 May 2025 and is scheduled for completion by 1 July 2025\. Five defined milestones guide progress through design, development, testing, and deployment.

### 1.2 Project Objective

The project is designed with the following key objectives:

1. Provide a secure and organized membership directory for Zon 20\.  
2. Simplify event registration, RSVP management, and attendance tracking.  
3. Maintain two-way communication via news and feedback forms.  
4. Showcase activity galleries.

These objectives were defined during the initiation phase and confirmed during discussions with the project sponsor and manager.

### 1.3 Project Contribution & Implications

#### For PeBS Zon 20:

* Digitally modernizes all core administrative operations.

* Improves communication efficiency and member tracking.

* Provides accurate data for decision-making and reporting to authorities.

  #### For the Development Team:

* Applies academic knowledge in real-world software and project management practices.

* Enhances teamwork, client communication, time management, and risk handling.

* Strengthens individual technical skills in development, testing, deployment, and documentation.

2.2 Team Contract

	The PeBS Management System project team comprises seven members, each with clearly defined roles and mutual agreements to ensure project success. Tengku Azrin serves as the Project Manager, responsible for coordinating the entire development process, managing communication with the client, organizing meetings, tracking progress, and resolving team issues. He ensures that all milestones are met on time and that team collaboration runs smoothly throughout the design, development, and deployment phases.

Danial, the UI/UX Designer, is tasked with creating a user-friendly and visually appealing interface. His work includes preparing wireframes, mockups, and design prototypes that align with user expectations and functional requirements. He collaborates closely with the front-end developer and the client to ensure that user interaction flows are intuitive, responsive, and accessible across devices.

Kamaputra and Hakimi share backend responsibilities. Kamaputra is specifically responsible for modules such as Member Registration & Login and Event Calendar & RSVP. Hakimi, on the other hand, manages modules including Authentication Middleware by User Role,  News & Announcements, Feedback Form, and Activity Gallery Upload. They work collaboratively, with Kamaputra assisting Hakimi in backend tasks when required. In addition to technical responsibilities, Kamaputra also serves as the Project Secretary, documenting meeting minutes, tracking progress, and ensuring consistent communication across the team.

Zaim, the QA Lead, ensures that the system meets the expected quality standards through structured test planning, bug tracking, and leading User Acceptance Testing (UAT). He documents defects, performs usability checks, and coordinates closely with developers to verify fixes. Furthermore, Faisal, the DevOps Engineer, manages the deployment infrastructure. He configures hosting environments, automates deployment workflows, and monitors server health to ensure smooth and secure application delivery.

Faisal, the DevOps Engineer, manages the hosting. He sets up the staging and production environments using DigitalOcean and monitors application performance post-deployment. Zaim, the QA Lead, is responsible for testing the application thoroughly and ensuring all functionalities meet quality standards. He prepares test cases, conducts functional and usability testing, and leads the UAT process. He documents all bugs and communicates with developers for resolution. Both Faisal and Zaim ensure that the system remains stable, secure, and maintainable.

All team members mutually agreed on their roles and responsibilities during the project’s initiation phase. The division of tasks was based on each member’s strengths, skill sets, and prior experience. This agreement was finalized through a team discussion, with everyone willingly accepting their responsibilities to ensure accountability and smooth collaboration. The team operates on mutual respect, with clear task delegation and shared ownership of the project's success.

Team collaboration is facilitated through daily WhatsApp updates for quick progress sharing and problem-solving. Structured meetings are held twice weekly (Tuesday and Wednesday) for mid-week development reviews, and a primary progress meeting is held every Friday to discuss milestones, blockers, and upcoming tasks. This consistent communication routine has helped maintain focus, alignment, and timely issue resolution throughout the project lifecycle.

### 2.3.5 Project Quality 

Quality planning ensures that the system meets both client expectations and technical standards. This includes defining measurable quality benchmarks and implementing structured testing processes.

#### 2.3.5.1 Quality Planning

Quality planning in the PeBS Management System project is systematically structured to ensure that both functional and non-functional requirements are consistently met. A dedicated Quality Assurance (QA) Lead oversees all testing activities from the initial unit testing phase through to the final User Acceptance Testing (UAT) stage. Quality Control (QC) measures are embedded throughout the development lifecycle, with regular code reviews and validation checkpoints ensuring early detection of issues.

The project defines clear and measurable quality success metrics, which include achieving a user satisfaction rate of 90% or higher, maintaining a bug rate of less than 5% during UAT, and ensuring that all complaints or feedback are addressed within 48 hours. These benchmarks serve as a guide for continuous quality monitoring and help ensure that the final system meets stakeholder expectations in both performance and usability.

#### 2.3.5.2 Cause-Effect Diagram 

The Cause-Effect (Ishikawa) Diagram for the PeBS Management System highlights six principal categories of potential defects, namely People, Process, Tools and Technology, Material, Environment, and Management. Each category was critically examined to identify underlying factors that could negatively impact the system's quality, reliability, and timely delivery.

In terms of the People category, the team recognized that limited experience among developers, particularly with the Laravel framework, could result in implementation errors. Furthermore, miscommunication between developers and designers had the potential to cause inconsistencies between functional modules and the intended design. To address these challenges, the team conducted regular coordination sessions, peer code reviews, and pair programming activities to strengthen collaboration and improve code accuracy.

The Process category was associated with risks arising from insufficient or poorly executed testing, incomplete documentation, and inadequate quality assurance (QA) cycles. These risks were mitigated through the implementation of regression testing, a structured QA plan, and continuous updates to technical and functional documentation. Regular assessments of test coverage were carried out to ensure that all functional requirements were thoroughly validated.

In the category of Tools and Technology, the potential for deployment failures, version conflicts, or misuse of development tools posed a risk to system stability. The team minimized these risks by standardizing the technology stack, enforcing strict version control practices using Git, and ensuring that environment configurations were properly maintained for both staging and production systems.

The Material category focused on risks linked to changes in project scope or incomplete client requirements, which could lead to rework or delays. These risks were mitigated through early validation of requirements, regular stakeholder reviews, and the maintenance of detailed change logs to ensure that all scope modifications were formally documented and approved.

Environmental factors, such as unstable Internet connections and distractions during remote development sessions, were also identified as potential obstacles to productivity. To overcome these challenges, the team adopted asynchronous communication methods, recorded meeting discussions for later reference, and defined sprint tasks clearly to maintain progress even when direct communication was disrupted.

Lastly, in the Management category, the lack of proper planning and ineffective communication were recognized as threats to timely project delivery. These issues were addressed by closely monitoring the project schedule using the Gantt chart, conducting regular progress meetings, and maintaining transparent communication channels to ensure that the entire team remained aligned with project objectives.

By systematically analyzing each of these categories and implementing targeted preventive measures, the project team successfully reduced the likelihood of defects, leading to improved reliability, quality, and stakeholder satisfaction in the final deliverable.

#### 2.3.6.2 RACI Chart 

The RACI chart is a critical project management tool used to clearly define and communicate the roles and responsibilities of team members throughout the project lifecycle. RACI stands for Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, and Informed. It ensures that for every key task or deliverable, each team member understands their specific role, thereby reducing ambiguity, preventing overlap, and improving project coordination. This structured approach to responsibility assignment enhances accountability and efficiency across the team.

In the context of the PeBS Management System project, the RACI chart outlines the distribution of responsibilities across various phases, including initiation, planning, execution, monitoring, and closure. Each project activity is assigned to one or more team members based on their roles and expertise. For example, the Project Manager is Accountable for activities such as goal definition, stakeholder coordination, and final system handover, whereas technical tasks such as backend development are assigned to the Backend Developers and Frontend Developer as Responsible parties.

Additionally, the chart reflects hybrid and specialized roles within the team. Kamaputra, who serves as both the Project Secretary and a Backend Developer, is shown as Responsible for documentation and coordination tasks, while also contributing technically to backend module development. This dual-role assignment is a practical reflection of real-world academic projects, where team members often support both administrative and technical aspects. Similarly, roles like UI/UX Designer and QA Lead are aligned with relevant tasks such as design finalization and system testing, ensuring the right expertise is consulted at the appropriate stages.

The RACI chart included in **Appendix C** was developed in alignment with best practices, as it avoids multiple Accountable parties for any single task and ensures proper distribution of workload. It enhances team communication by identifying who needs to be consulted or informed throughout the process. Overall, the RACI framework provided a clear structure for decision-making and task execution, allowing the PeBS project team to maintain clarity, collaboration, and control from start to finish.

#### 2.3.7.3 Performance Reporting 

Performance reporting played a crucial role in tracking project health and ensuring that all activities remained aligned with the planned scope, schedule, and quality expectations. The PeBS Management System team adopted a structured approach to performance monitoring through various formal and informal reporting tools, implemented on a weekly basis.

The primary tools used for performance reporting included weekly progress reports. These reports ensured that team members remained accountable and informed of each other’s responsibilities. Sprint reviews were conducted during the Friday meetings and served as a reflective platform for the team to evaluate deliverables completed during the sprint cycle. These reviews were stored and shared through Google Docs, enabling version control and real-time collaboration.

In parallel, a structured issue log was maintained by the QA Lead to record bugs, usability issues, and system defects encountered during development and testing. This log provided transparency on the types of challenges faced and enabled the developers to prioritize and resolve issues effectively. The QA Lead also tracked defect resolution timelines, aligning with the quality success metric of resolving user complaints or bugs within 48 hours.

A burndown chart, derived from the Gantt chart and project plan, visually tracks planned progress versus actual progress. It allowed the team to identify delays early and take corrective actions to keep the project on track. Finally, all performance reports were evaluated against pre-defined success metrics, such as achieving less than 5% bug rate during UAT, attaining over 90% user satisfaction, and ensuring RSVP and complaint response times below 48 hours. These reporting mechanisms not only supported data-driven decision-making but also provided the stakeholders with confidence in the project’s progress and quality.

### **3.1 Product Report**

#### 3.1.1 Overview

The PeBS Management System is a centralized, mobile-responsive web-based platform tailored for the operational needs of PeBS Zon 20\. The system provides secure access, efficient event coordination, real-time member data visibility, and feedback management for three primary user roles: Super Admin, Admin, and User. The platform enhances transparency, accountability, and accessibility in youth activity management under the Shah Alam City Council (MBSA).

#### 3.1.2 Requirements

##### 3.1.2.1 User Requirements

The PeBS Management System supports three primary user roles: Youth Users, Admins, and Super Admins. Each role has distinct functionalities and responsibilities, and the system is designed to fulfil the unique requirements of each group.

#### A. Youth Users (General Users)

Youth Users are the target end-users of the system, typically members of PeBS Zon 20 who participate in programs and activities. Their requirements include:

* Ability to register an account securely using email and password credentials.

* Ability to log in and log out of the system using secure authentication.

* Access to a dashboard displaying upcoming activities, announcements, and gallery.

* Ability to view available activities, including title, date, location, and description.

* Ability to register or RSVP for activities and view their registration status.

* Ability to submit feedback after attending an activity.

* Access to announcements, including real-time updates from Admins or Super Admins.

* Seamless experience across desktop and mobile devices (responsive design).

  #### B. Admins

Admins are authorized representatives responsible for managing activities and engaging with youth users. Their system-related needs include:

* Access to a role-specific Admin Dashboard with management tools.

* Ability to create, update, delete, and restore activities (CRUD operations).

* Ability to track user participation, including registration lists.

* Ability to send announcements or notifications to users regarding programs or updates.

* Access to view and manage user feedback submitted after activities.

* Ability to upload media (images/videos) to the gallery for specific activities.

* Mobile and desktop access to ensure flexibility in managing events.

  #### C. Super Admins

Super Admins have the highest level of access and are typically responsible for overall system oversight and account management. Their requirements include:

* Ability to create, manage, and delete Admin accounts.

* Ability to restore deleted activities or records for data recovery.

* Monitor and audit user engagement, feedback submissions, and system notifications.

* Manage system-wide announcements or urgent notifications.

  ### 

  ### **3.1.2.2 Functional Requirements**

The fundamental actions and features of the PeBS Management System are outlined in the functional requirements. These requirements outline the functions each user role, like Super Admin, Admin, and User, can carry out within the system and are grouped by system modules.

#### 1\. User Registration

* The user must be able to create an account by providing their full name, email address, and password.

* The system must validate user input and prevent duplicate registrations.

* Registration confirmation must be provided upon successful account creation.

  #### 2\. User Login and Authentication

* Super Admins, Admins, and Users must be able to securely log in using their credentials.

* Laravel Breeze will be used to handle authentication, session control, and secure routing.

* Role-based redirection must occur upon login, directing users to the appropriate dashboard.  
  

  #### 3\. Role-Based Dashboards

* Super Admin Dashboard:

  * Perform CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) operations on Admin accounts.

  * View all registered activities and user participation data.

  * Restore deleted activity records.

* Admin Dashboard:

  * Manage activities including creation, update, deletion, and restoration.

  * View participant lists and feedback.

  * Manage media uploads.  
    

* User Dashboard:

  * View available activities with details such as date, location, and description.

  * Register (RSVP) for activities and view participation history.

  * Submit post-activity feedback and view announcements.

  #### 4\. Activity Management

* Admins and Super Admins must be able to create, update, delete (soft delete), and restore activities.

* Each activity entry must support fields such as title, description, date, time, location, and optional media.

* Users must be able to register for listed activities and receive confirmation messages.

* Deleted activities should be restorable for audit trail and data recovery purposes.

  #### 5\. Feedback Management

* Registered users must be able to submit feedback after participating in an activity.

* Admins must be able to access and review submitted feedback for analysis and reporting.

  #### 6\. Notification and Announcement System

* Admins must be able to publish announcements and send notifications to users.

* Notifications may be delivered through in-system announcement banner.

  #### 7\. Gallery and Media Management

* Admins must be able to upload images to associate with specific activities.

* Media must be stored in a gallery module and categorized by event.

* Images should be viewable by Users through the Activity Gallery.

  #### 8\. System Responsiveness

* The system must follow a mobile-first design principle and render correctly on smartphones, tablets, and desktops.

* All forms and dashboards must adapt responsively to various screen sizes and maintain usability.  
  


  ### **3.1.2.3 Data Requirements**

**Database Schema :**

* **users**  
   id, name, email, password, is\_admin, is\_super\_admin, timestamps  
* **activities**  
   id, title, description, date, picture, location, deleted\_at, timestamps  
* **gallery**  
   id, image, activity\_id (FK)  
* **activity\_user (pivot table)**  
   activity\_id, user\_id, feedback  
* **announcement**  
   id, title, description, image, timestamps


### **3.1.3.1 Proposed Software Architecture & Development Methodology**

#### **A. Software Architecture**

The PeBS Management System is developed using a **three-tier Model-View-Controller (MVC)** architecture, implemented through the Laravel framework. This architectural design promotes modular development, code reusability, and scalability.

* Presentation Layer:  
   The user interface is built using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, rendered through Laravel Blade templates. This layer is responsible for displaying data and capturing user inputs across various devices using a mobile-responsive layout.

* Application Layer:  
   This middle layer handles the system’s logic and request processing. It utilizes Laravel Controllers to route user actions, validate data, manage user roles, and coordinate between the front-end and database.

* Data Layer:  
   The system employs a MySQL database, accessed through Laravel's Eloquent ORM (Object Relational Mapper). This layer manages persistent data storage, including user records, activity logs, media files, and system feedback.

#### **B. Development Methodology**

The Prototype Model was adopted as the primary software development methodology for this project. This model is suitable for projects involving active user interaction, evolving requirements, and iterative refinement.

![][image3]

Key Characteristics of the Prototype Model Implementation:

#### 1\. Requirements Analysis

* During this first phase, the development team gathered important system requirements by holding multiple consultation sessions with the PeBS Zon 20 client representative. The main topics of discussion were understanding the shortcomings of manual procedures and determining the essential features required on the digital platform. Role-based dashboards (User, Admin, Super Admin), RSVP management, announcements, feedback submission, and member registration were among them. The system's scope was established at this phase, which matched stakeholder expectations with technical viability.

  #### 2\. Quick Design

* During the Quick Design phase, the development team utilized Figma, a collaborative web-based design tool, to create a low-fidelity user interface (UI) prototype based on the requirements gathered from initial discussions. The design included essential screens such as the login page, user registration page, Super Admin dashboard, Admin dashboard, User dashboard, activity listing page, activity creation and management forms, RSVP registration interface, feedback submission form, gallery module and announcement panel. These wireframes highlighted the system's overall navigation flow and visual structure. Although the prototype was not yet functional, it enabled the client to visualize the layout, screen flow, and feature distribution of the complete system. This stage successfully reduced ambiguity and established a common visual reference for the subsequent development phases.

  #### 3\. Build Prototype

* The Laravel framework was used to create a partly functional model of the system. Important functionality, including user registration, authentication, and dashboard access for various user roles, was all present in this prototype. The objective was to illustrate interaction logic, page transitions, and role-based access control by simulating real system behaviour with sample data. Early in the development cycle, the customer was able to engage with the system and comprehend its practical flow of operations.

  #### 4\. User/Client Evaluation

* The client was shown the prototype for a preliminary assessment. The customer offered input on usability issues, feature gaps, and preferred layouts. Additionally, feedback on notification flows, user feedback monitoring, and activity management visibility was obtained. The group noted areas that needed improvement and methodically recorded the comments. The client's continued involvement and the system's continued alignment with user expectations were guaranteed by this review.

  #### 5\. Refining Prototype

* In response to the client’s evaluation, the development team made iterative enhancements to the prototype. These refinements included adjustments to navigation menus, more intuitive user flows, implementation of real-time RSVP features, and improvement of the feedback form layout. Admin functionality was also expanded to include user management and gallery upload features. The refined prototype brought the system closer to the final product by aligning visual and functional aspects with real client needs.

  #### 6\. Client Approval

* After several refinement cycles, the final prototype version was reviewed and formally approved by the PeBS client. The prototype at this stage represented a close approximation of the full system, incorporating all essential modules and interface behaviors. The client’s approval marked the transition point from prototype development to full system implementation. This milestone validated that the solution was well-understood, agreed upon, and ready for complete development.

  #### 7\. System Development

* Following client approval, the system entered full-scale development. The development team translated the approved prototype into a production-ready web application. This phase involved implementing all back-end logic, securing APIs, integrating database models, and deploying responsive UI components. Additional modules, such as feedback  and announcement were also completed. Code versioning and task tracking were managed collaboratively using GitHub and shared project documentation.

  #### 8\. System Testing

* Upon completion of development, rigorous Quality Assurance (QA) and User Acceptance Testing (UAT) were conducted. Test cases covered functional, performance, security, and usability aspects. The QA Lead identified and logged issues through a structured defect tracking sheet. Any detected bugs or inconsistencies were resolved promptly in collaboration with the developers. UAT was performed with actual users to ensure the system met real-world expectations before deployment.

  #### 9\. System Maintenance

* After testing and handover, a maintenance phase was initiated to ensure system stability. The team continued monitoring the system, fixing residual bugs, and implementing minor enhancements based on client feedback. The deployment environment was optimized using a DigitalOcean VPS to ensure uptime, scalability, and performance. This phase ensured the PeBS Management System remained functional, secure, and user-friendly beyond the final delivery.

## 3.1.3.3 Quality Attributes & Assessment Process

## The PeBS Management System emphasizes quality through several measurable attributes, each of which has an associated assessment method to ensure that system expectations are met throughout development and deployment.

### Quality Attributes and Their Assessments:

| Quality Attribute | Description | Assessment Methodology |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| Functionality | The system performs all required tasks correctly. | Functional testing, unit testing, and acceptance testing with clients. |
| Usability | Easy-to-navigate interface for all user roles. | Heuristic evaluation, usability testing with users. |
| Reliability | The system runs consistently without failure. | Stress testing and error rate tracking during the QA phase. |
| Performance | Fast page load time and real-time RSVP response. | Performance benchmarks, load testing. |
| Security | User data is protected with proper authentication and validation. | Security audits, input validation, and penetration testing. |
| Maintainability | The code is modular and easy to update or fix. | Code review, use of MVC framework (Laravel), and documentation checks. |
| Portability | Works across devices and browsers (responsive). | Cross-browser testing, mobile-first design checks. |

### Assessment Process Steps:

1. ## Define Quality Benchmarks:-

   The team established clear quality benchmarks to measure success. A maximum bug rate of less than 5% during UAT was targeted, with a response time of under 2 seconds for user submissions. Additionally, achieving a user satisfaction score of over 90% post-deployment was set as a key performance indicator to ensure usability and reliability.

2. ## Conduct Testing:-

   ## The QA Lead prepared comprehensive test cases and defect sheets to guide functional and regression testing. These tests were conducted during development sprints to quickly detect issues. UAT sessions were organized in collaboration with stakeholders and youth representatives, ensuring the system met real-world requirements and user expectations.

3. ## Monitor and Review:-

   Weekly performance reviews were conducted during progress meetings to assess testing outcomes and track quality metrics. A feedback loop was established to facilitate quick resolution of reported issues, helping maintain the project's quality standards and preventing defects from escalating.

4. ## Post-Deployment Evaluation:-

   After deployment, the team collected user feedback via the built-in system form and tracked usage logs and bug reports. A final QA report was prepared, documenting any residual issues and confirming that all key quality benchmarks were met. Sign-off was secured based on this evaluation.

### **3.2 Gantt Chart (Plan vs Actual)**

Most of the activities, including project kickoff, finalising the plan, UI/UX design, developing backend and frontend modules, and setting up hosting, were completed as scheduled. ### **3.3 Financial Report (Budget vs Actual Expenses)**

The financial planning and execution of the PeBS Management System project were managed with precision to ensure optimal use of the allocated RM500 budget. As an academic project, all expenses were simulated for accountability and project documentation purposes, reflecting realistic needs for infrastructure, tools, and basic administrative resources.

The major expense categories included manpower value representation, web hosting, and contingency spending. The hosting cost was actual and essential for staging the system, which used a DigitalOcean VPS. While the team initially considered a free domain, they later opted to purchase a custom domain for RM30 to enhance presentation and realism during the demonstration phase.

The contingency fund was fully utilized for printing costs, internet data reloads, and backup flash storage used during UAT and documentation handover. The overall spending met the full RM500 budget, with no overrun or surplus. This reflects responsible and balanced financial management.

## **5.0 CONCLUSION**

### 5.1 Lessons Learned and Reflection

The PeBS Management System project emphasized the importance of structured project management methodologies, effective communication, and strong teamwork. Throughout the project, the team learned that early engagement with stakeholders and frequent feedback sessions on wireframes and prototypes helped reduce rework and ensured alignment with user expectations. Centralized documentation and version control improved collaboration between backend, frontend, and quality assurance teams, allowing them to work seamlessly despite overlapping tasks and deadlines.

Reflecting on team performance, each member contributed significantly to the overall success of the project. Kamaputra’s role as both a backend developer and project secretary ensured that technical development and project documentation were well-coordinated. Hakimi and Fikri effectively collaborated on backend and frontend integration, while Danial’s UI/UX designs improved user experience. Zaim’s structured QA approach minimized defects, and Faisal’s work on deployment and hosting ensured a stable production environment. The collective efforts of the team, supported by consistent communication and timely problem-solving, were crucial in delivering the system successfully.

### 5.2 Recommendation for Improvement

For further projects, the team suggests using automated testing frameworks and tools to increase test coverage and accuracy while cutting down on manual quality checks.  During the start-up stage, it would also be advantageous to implement a thorough risk management framework in order to anticipate and address possible issues.  By increasing the frequency of client reviews at significant stages, last-minute modifications may be minimized and deliverables can be further guaranteed to stay closely aligned with stakeholder expectations.

The team also suggests improving documentation practices by adopting a more structured versioning system for technical specifications, user manuals, and test cases. Enhanced knowledge-sharing sessions among team members, especially between backend and frontend developers, would further improve cross-functional collaboration. In addition, incorporating post-sprint retrospectives could help capture lessons learned in real time and drive continuous process improvement.

### 5.3 Conclusion

To sum up, the PeBS Management System was successfully delivered with all core functionalities implemented, thoroughly tested, and validated within the agreed project timeline. Despite encountering minor delays during the QA and documentation phases, the project team demonstrated strong adaptability by reallocating resources and adjusting schedules to ensure that all milestones were achieved before the final handover.

The collaborative effort among all team members, supported by structured communication methods, formal progress reporting, and performance monitoring, was a key factor in overcoming challenges and maintaining quality standards. Stakeholder feedback received during UAT sessions was effectively incorporated into the final product, ensuring that the system meets both functional requirements and user expectations.

Overall, the final system is ready for stakeholder approval and deployment. It not only aligns with the objectives set out in the initial project plan but also reflects a high standard of quality, usability, and maintainability that positions it for long-term success and scalability.
